05592nam a22010575i 9781501509902DE-B159720210927121507.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210927t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2020951352  a97815015099027 a10.1515/97815015099022doi  a(DE-B1597)494783  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aPN6147b.A44 2021 7aLAN0040002bisacsh1 aAlsadi, Wejdan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Multimodal Rhetoric of Humour in Saudi Media Cartoons /cWejdan Alsadi, Martin Howard. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (VIII, 178 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHumor Research [HR] ;v1200tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- t1 Introduction -- t2 Humour, media and multimodality -- t3 Cartoons: A multimodal genre -- t4 Intertextuality: Allusion and parody in cartoons -- t5 Multimodal metaphor -- t6 The interaction between multimodal metaphor and metonymy -- t7 Juxtaposition and exaggeration -- t8 Conclusion. Speaking images in a Saudi context: What cartoons reveal -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCartoons, as a form of humour and entertainment, are a social product which are revealing of different social and political practices that prevail in a society, humourised and satirised by the cartoonist. This book advances research on cartoons and humour in the Saudi context. It contributes to the growing multimodal research on non-interactional humour in the media that benefits from traditional theories of verbal humour. The study analyses the interaction between visual and verbal modes, highlighting the multimodal manifestations of the rhetorical devices frequently employed to create humour in English-language cartoons collected from the Saudi media. The multimodal analysis shows that the frequent rhetorical devices such as allusions, parody, metaphor, metonymy, juxtaposition, and exaggeration take a form which is woven between the visual and verbal modes, and which makes the production of humorous and satirical effect more unique and interesting. The analysis of the cartoons across various thematic categories further offers a window into contemporary Saudi society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aArt, Saudi Arabian. 0aMass mediazSaudi Arabia. 0aRhetoriczSaudi Arabia. 0aWit and humor, Pictorial. 0aWit and humor. 4aArabisch. 4aEthnographie. 4aHumor. 4aMedien. 4aPop Kultur. 4aSemiotik. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Communication Studies.2bisacsh  aArabic.  aCultural Studies.  aEthnographic Studies.  aHumour Studies.  aMedia Studies.  aPop Culture.  aSemiotics.1 aHoward, Martin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Ebook Package English 2021z978311075072008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2021 Part 1z978311075070608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDe Gruyter Mouton Frontlist 2021z978311074943408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2021 Englishz978311075411708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Linguistics 2021z9783110753882oZDB-23-DSP0 cEPUBz97815015098410 cprintz978150151672640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150150990240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501509902423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501509902/original  a978-3-11-074943-4  De Gruyter Mouton Frontlist 2021b2